### For Loop

The `for` loop is ideal when the number of iterations is known beforehand. It consolidates initialization, condition, and increment in one line.

---

### Basic Syntax

```cpp
for (initialization; condition; increment) {
  // Code to repeat
}
```

---

### Example

```cpp
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  cout << i << " ";
}
// Output: 0 1 2 3 4
```

---

### Parts of For Loop

| Part | Purpose | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| Initialization | Sets starting value | `int i = 0` |
| Condition | Checked before each iteration | `i < 10` |
| Increment | Runs after each iteration | `i++` |

---

### Variations

**Multiple variables:**
```cpp
for (int i = 0, j = 10; i < j; i++, j--) {
  cout << i << "-" << j << " ";
}
```

**Omitting parts:**
```cpp
int i = 0;
for (; i < 5; ) {  // All parts optional
  cout << i++;
}
```

**Range-based for (C++11):**
```cpp
int arr[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
for (int x : arr) {
  cout << x << " ";
}
```

---

> **Key Point:** Use range-based `for` loops when iterating over containers. They are safer and more readable than index-based loops.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    cout << i << " ";
  }
  cout << endl;

  // Range-based
  int nums[] = {10, 20, 30};
  for (int n : nums) {
    cout << n << " ";
  }
  return 0;
}
